content.description: This inside corner flaring crack can be tricky but is a fun climb.
content.protection: .4 to #2 for leading.  A #5 or #6 would work for the wide section but isn't necessary.  Trees and cracks for an anchor.
content.location: Inside corner to the climbers left of Mickey Mantles.

content.description: A beautiful finger crack!  The crux of the route is the wider part a third of the way up.
content.protection: Anchor off the cracks and trees at the top of the cliff.
content.location: Climbers left of Thrombus on the flat face.  The finger crack extends to the top of the cliff.

content.description: Climb to the small roof and then up the seam.  The crux is near the top of the route.
content.protection: #4, 0.4, #1, 0.75. Anchor from cracks & trees at the top of the cliff.
content.location: Climbers right of Mickey Mantles on the face.

content.description: Start by mantling the broken ledges to the main wall. Climb up to a horizontal hand jam. From here you can stick the dyno straight up, or go slightly left to slick crimps. Finish by working up the smaller ledges angling up and left.
content.protection: thin passive or top rope anchor

content.description: This is a great route of all mantles that looks a lot easier than it really is.
content.protection: Toprope from the wide cracks and trees at the top of the cliff.
content.location: Climbers right of the inside corner flared crack (Thrombus).  Look for the ledges.

content.description: An amazing left to right traversing crack system that finishes on an exposed knife edge compression arete. One of the most fun 5.9 climbs I've done in Taylor's.
content.protection: .3"-2" cams, a few c3's, and nuts.
content.location: Climbers right of crossover artist, 50ft climbers left of Thrombus/Rod's Teeth

content.description: Tricky little sequence.  The awkward angle of the arete makes you use your brain on how to do it efficiently
content.protection: top rope anchor. (old description says "or thin passive". There isn't anywhere to actually put gear. Leading this would be a solo on a rope).
content.location: The arete right of Skin of Rod's Teeth

content.description: Start with a slightly overhanging face, then up a finger crack to a very interesting exit over a bulge. finish up an easier hand crack.
content.protection: Thin passive or top rope anchor
content.location: Start near the junction of the wall with the river.

content.description: This area is not visited often but has a few great routes.  I think many people walk by and never know that there is climbing here.  Warming up on Thrombus and Mickey Mantles and then having some fun on the harder cracks makes for a great afternoon.
